@pwige , thanks for re-checking, but I just realised why this is happening.

Increasing the MTU should help with traffic originating directly in the container, and I still think changing it by default is a good idea.  However in your use case the traffic is originating somewhere else and is forwarded over the Wireguard tunnel.  The MSS will be set by that remote system, constrained by the minimum path MTU.  That's probably going to be limited to 1500 by some Ethernet link along the way, and if not it will be constrained by Wireguard's own MTU.

Wireguard is forwarding at the packet/L3 level, so there's no stream coalescing going on there.  Pasta will theoretically coalesce when it forwards, but that's not particularly useful because we still have the overhead of dealing with all the small packets on the container side.

Unfortunately, this is kind of fundamental: the design case for pasta was a single guest - or maybe a small network of guests - that are otherwise isolated from the world.  With a tunnel in there, we effectively have the entire internet on the container side, which takes away one major strategy for keeping our overhead down (large MTU).  Theoretically, if the traffic is originating from _immediately_ on the other side of the wireguard link, it could be mitigated by increasing the MTU of the wireguard link.  However, that's unlikely to work in practice, since it would require wireguard to use very large UDP packets which have to be fragmented.

@sbrivio-rh's `SO_RCVLOWAT` idea might help a bit, but I suspect not all that much.  Alas, at this point I can't think of much to do beyond concluding that pasta is poorly suited to this particular workload, at least with an old machine on a fast link.

@kalelkenobi since in your case there seems to a regression, I think in your case there's something additional going on, so there's better hope for a fix.  @Rivers47 @grtcdr the above notes are not relevant to your cases, those appear to have a different cause that we're still debugging.

